# arvo-numeric-contracts. Design

The numeric-op trait declarations. Every trait here is `pub const trait`.
Default-impl bodies for the standard cases live in the `arvo` facade
(where they can compose `Bits<N, S>`, `UFixed`, `IFixed`); concrete
overrides per primitive container live in `arvo-bits` and the
implementation crates that need them. `#![no_std]`, no alloc.

Depends on `notko`, `arvo-storage`, `arvo-bits-contracts`.

## Abs

```rust
pub const trait Abs {
    type Output;
    fn abs(self) -> Self::Output;
}
```

Absolute value. Output is `Self` for unsigned types, `Self` for
signed types where the type can represent the absolute value of its
domain (one-complement edge cases excluded by the type system or
handled per-impl).

## Recip

```rust
pub const trait Recip {
    type Output;
    fn recip(self) -> Self::Output;
}
```

Reciprocal `1/x`. Domain restrictions per concrete impl. For
`UFixed<I, F, S>` with F=0, recip returns a `UFixed<0, I, S>` (the
fractional dual). For F>0, recip returns a same-shape value via
fixed-point reciprocal.

## Sqrt

```rust
pub const trait Sqrt {
    type Output;
    fn sqrt(self) -> Self::Output;
}
```

Square root. Domain is non-negative values; signed-input impls
clamp negatives to zero or panic per impl-specific contract.

## TotalOrd

```rust
pub const trait TotalOrd {
    fn total_cmp(self, other: Self) -> Ordering;
}
```

Total ordering. Distinct from `core::cmp::Ord` so float-bearing arvo
types can implement a strict-NaN-policy ordering without conflicting
with the partial `core::PartialOrd`.

## FromConstant

```rust
pub const trait FromConstant<const C: USize> {
    fn from_constant() -> Self;
}
```

Compile-time constant constructor. Used by macros and bitfield
generators that want to inject typed constants into expressions.

## Predicate family

```rust
pub const trait Predicate {
    fn test(self) -> Bool;
}
```

The base predicate trait. Composes with named subtypes (`IsZero`,
`IsPositive`, `IsNonZero`, etc.) per #122. Each named predicate is a
`pub const trait` extending `Predicate`. Concrete impls live on the
relevant arvo numeric type families.

